title: For Sale:  AK RPK Norinco, w/Bi-pod, flash surpress. long barrel
postcontent:
RPK MFG by Norinco, Better Than balkin/east europe or usa made units 21.5 inch .668 dia heavy barrel 1.5mm heavy stamped.  Much cleaner mfg than most europe balkin made. 

THE CONDITION IS EXCELLENT 
Caliber 7,62x39 mm
Length of Barrel: 21"

In mid-1950s Soviet army started trials for a new infantry weapons system to replace the 7.62x39 SKScarbines, AKassault rifles and RPD LMGs.Several designers submitted their designs, which included both assault rifle and machine rifle / LMG – basically the same weapon as the companion rifle but with a longer, heavier barrel and with larger capacity, but still compatible, magazines. In 1961, Soviet army has chosen the Kalashnikov system, comprising of a modified AKM assault rifle and RPK squad automatic weapon (machine rifle / light machine gun). RPK stands for Ruchnoy Pulemjot Kalashnikova- Kalashnikov hand-held (light) machine gun. Copies of the RPK are produced in several countries, that also made AK type rifles.

The RPK is a gas operated, magazine fed, air cooled, selective fire weapon.The basic action, with a long-stroke gas piston located above the barrel and a rotating bolt, is similar to that of the Kalashnikov assault rifle. The trigger unit and safety is also the same,therefore the RPK fires from a closed bolt in both semi-automatic and automatic modes. The barrel is permanently fixed to the receiver and cannot be replaced in the field.
Ammunition feed is from magazines only.The magazine interface is same as on the Kalashnikov assault rifle in the same caliber, and RPK and AKM magazines are interchangeable. However, the standard magazines for RPK are of extended capacity. The most common are curved box magazines holding 40 rounds of ammunition. 

Standard sights of RPK are basically similar to that of the AKM rifle, with hooded post front and tangent type rear sight, marked for ranges between 100 and 1000 meters. However, the RPK rear sight also includes a windage adjustment mechanism. 

RPK machine guns are fitted with integral folding bipods made from steel stampings.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Over new retail price used firearms FS/FT
postcontent:
I have an extensive collection of firearms, dating from WWII to modern. All of them are used and have been fired. I'm looking for some idiot to give me more than what they can buy the same weapon for at a retail store. 

To 90% of the posters on here - If you didn't receive the firearm directly from the manufacturer, or a legitimate distributor, it is not new, regardless if you've fired it or not. This alone drops the value 10% below market price.

To everyone else - your firearm is not worth new retail price, or more. I can't even count the number of used firearms on here people are asking ridiculous money for. Theres $400-500 SKS's, (which are a $200-$300 gun tops at major retailers), TCP's and Sigma's for $300+ used. (which are $250-$280 NEW), glocks, sigs, kel-tecs, rugers are the same story, and don't get me started on shotguns. Mossbergs are $300 max new, provided they come with 2 barrells, and I've seen plenty wanting more than that for a single barrell.

Bottom line is this - Unless you are trying to sell to inelligible owners, no buyer with half a brain, and legitimate money, is going to pay you a premium over the NEW price, period. If you overpaid, that's your problem. Don't bother advertising your used piece for $20-$100 over what you can buy a new one for. It's basic economics, sure right now the market is on the fritz, but it's an election year, it doesn't make your $200 gun worth $500, sorry!! 

If you want to sell a firearm quickly to a legal and eligible buyer, a good starting price is 3/4's of current retail, NOT 150-200% more. QUIT ASKING MORE THAN MSRP FOR YOUR USED FIREARM, SOMEONE MAY ACTUALLY BUY IT FOR MARKET PRICE!!

I'm not selling, but I'll throw some guns and prices out there *quality pieces*, comparable to what I've scene on here: Russian Mosin/Nagain M91/54 with al accessories, Tula manufacture, Round Reciever, - $350; Hungarian and Chek Makarov's - $500 each; 1895 Nagant revolver, with holster, and cleaning rod, Tula - $350; Taurus TCP 380 with 2 mags and 2 holsters - $400; Hi-Points .45 acp and 9mm carbine with a tactical stock and extended mag - $750; Jimenez .380 and 9mm - $450; RG 22LR -$200; Winchester 870 Wingmaster 12 ga. - $750; Savage 22LR rifle with scope - $375.

Honestly, I wouldn't meet someone in person, or sell any of those firearms at these prices. That deal would have bad news written all over it, and from the scammers I've seen on here, I wouldn't risk my life to sell a firearm I have no desire to get rid of...

The Mosin-Nagant (Russian: ???????? ??????) is a bolt-action, magazine fed, military rifle that was used by the armed forces of Imperial Russia and later the Soviet Union and various Eastern bloc nations. Also known as the Three-Line Rifle (Russian: ???????????? ????????), it was the first to use the 7.62x54mmR cartridge. As a front-line rifle, the Mosin-Nagant served in various forms from 1891 until the 1960s in many Eastern European nations, when the sniper rifle variant was replaced by the SVD (Russian: ??????????? ???????? ????????? — "Snajperskaja Vintovka Dragunova"). The Mosin-Nagant is still used in many conflicts due to its ruggedness and the vast number produced during World War II.

Model 1944 Carbine — this carbine was introduced into service in late 1943 and remained in production until 1948. Its specifications are very similar to the M1938, with the major exception of having a permanently affixed, folding quadrangular-bladed bayonet. These were in use not only by the USSR, but also its various satellite nations.
